Â @ReconFXÂ  I mean its a bit much to say she was off at many points, at some yes but not a lot. Also you can still be off key even if pitch correction is used, depends on the kind of that is used. On many correction types it is enough to be off by half a note for the pitch correction to correct the wrong way. I think it's safe to say that nowadays there are not many performances left where there is absolutely no correction used at all, especially if the vocal has to harmonice with a backing vocal/track because that is really noticeable if it's of by even a little bit. Also some times the artists won't even know the engineers used it and they could be using one for the stream but not live because live sound is much more forgiving. So I'm pretty sure they used some kind of pitch correction somewhere in the chain and if they did it was a very subtle one (in my personal taste, the best kind). Which absolutely does not take away from the artists performance because just like eq it's just a correction for stuff the artist can't really control. I see that there are a lot of comments discussing about the performer's voice cracks and such but considering the environment she did fantastic. The stadium there is completely open so voice doesn't ring. Also Riot Games probably took out the excited shoutings of the crowd (you see how throughout most of the performance there aren't any shouts or screams?) So in the live performance probably had a lot of noises. Considering that the singer's own voice doesn't ring back to her and the crowd is making noise she is at a state where she cannot hear her voice! The sheer fact that she was able to get most of the vocal flow of the song while not being able to hear her own voice is amazing! So yeah this is what heard from another person. To anyone commenting hologram, this is not a hologram. This is augmented reality
Hologram technology maybe?

The dragon was Augmented Reality (AR) - the dragon was rendered on top of the camera feed in real time, meaning people in the stadium couldn't see it. The 2019 opening used holograms on gauze which is a bit like a two-way mirror - if you're on the side being lit (or projected on to), you can see it, but when it's dark on your side and light on the other side, you can see through. They used projectors to display video on the gauze, and kept the light off the gauze when it wasn't in use. Unlike the AR dragon, the audience could see the same thing as we saw at home (although they may not have the best perspective on it.)
CGI
Anh Tran Nhat  Pause at 2:58 It's on the screen and on the stadium. I'm not doubting it's AR, but I can't see how this shot works.

At 2:49, the camera pans up and we're looking at the sky. Even if the audience only sees what's on the big screen and we who watch it on YouTube or TV see it in both places, I'm still curious how that works. That's the real sun shining down on the stadium. How do they get the dragon's shadow in the right place?
du bu cgi
Â @scottisittÂ  The stadium screen is showing a copy of the stream, which has the dragon imposed on it. It will be lagging behind a little bit, but not enough to be noticable in this case.

Â @scottisittÂ  I don't know specifically how they did it here, but one way that this sort of thing can work is that you attach something to the camera to enable it to know where it is and where it's looking in the scene, and you use that to place it in your virtual scene. For example, you build your stadium in your virtual world, put the sun in the right place based on the time of day of the show, animate the flight path of your dragon, etc - that would all need to be done in advance. You then render the dragon from a 3D model to a 2D image as seen from the position and angle your camera is currently at, which you'd feed into the software. Rather than rendering it on top of the virutal stadium, however, you render it on top of the the camera image.

"Legends never die" is a term used to symbolize the influence that they had over someone or a group of people. When an influence is powerful enough, then they will always be remembered and passed down by memory. Thus they never truly die because their names and deeds are still be carried down in history. Think of the many people we still talk about in history. They may be long dead but the fact is their names are still being carried after years, even centuries after. The term "Legends Never Die" isnt literal, it's about "Remembering A Legacy".
